attributes.title: Nike Free Plus 2
attributes.longdescription:
As the creative force behind the Nike Free Plus 2 launch, we took the helm in crafting an immersive retail experience that spanned across Nike's influencer stores in Tokyo, London, and the 21 Mercer store in New York City. Leveraging the visual core we devised for the campaign, we transformed each retail space into a dynamic showcase that echoed the fusion of high-end innovation and foundational technology at the heart of the Nike Free brand.

A pivotal element of our retail strategy was the innovative use of data visualization, drawing from a year's worth of Nike+ running data across NYC, Tokyo, and London. We developed an application that not only highlighted individual city runs in a random fashion but also painted a vivid picture of each city through the runners' chosen paths. This approach not only showcased the physical journeys but also conceptually highlighted the urban tapestry—streets, parks, and neighborhoods—through the collective athletic endeavors, forming a living, evolving map.

For the campaign's visual statement, we created an expansive halftone pattern mural, inspired by the campaign's photography. This wasn't just any halftone pattern; we engineered a custom application that utilized pie charts for the dots, infusing the artwork with a deep technological essence that belied its simple appearance. Further embracing the theme of low-fi technology, we experimented with Moire patterns, crafting several designs that were printed onto hanging glass, spaced a few inches apart. This technique created an engaging visual phenomenon, captivating both pedestrians outside and customers within, as they observed the Moire effect come to life.

In every aspect, from data-driven visuals to innovative use of traditional techniques, we didn't just create a retail space; we crafted an experience—a narrative that every visitor could step into and feel the pulse of the Nike Free brand, driven by technology, athleticism, and community.

attributes.title: Helix
attributes.longdescription:
At a time of exponential innovation in biotechnology, a focus on leveraging genomics at the scale of populations made Helix a vital repository of data and information during the COVID-19 pandemic.

As Helix refined its approach to messaging and other aspects of their brand, the technology they used for publishing content was fragmented and tough to use. Aleph engaged in an ambitious effort to shape a new visual presence around their existing identity, and to deliver a stable-but-malleable content platform to meet a diverse set of requirements with enterprise-level confidence.

This migration presented us with a few major challenges from the word “go”. We were tasked with refining the online presentation of Helix’s identity and messaging through a comprehensive design process. In addition, we needed to conceptualize and build a tech platform that would modernize their publishing workflows while deftly handling several years of legacy content.

Aleph dsdelivered on a purposeful project plan, including the migration of content from multiple legacy platforms, a broad approach to content strategy and management, and a complete interactive design system featuring well-documented processes, usage and development recommendations. We’re proud to support Helix in their mission to innovate with population genomics, and excited to see what’s next.

attributes.title: Tracy Chapman
attributes.longdescription:
When I got the email from Tracy Chapman's agent, I was a little caught off gaurd. I was suprised and excited but also thought the design directions we had been taking at OrdinaryKids may be too far out there. As always, I was rady to jump on a plane and head down.

Tracy met with my in her studio. We breifly chatted about project details but quickly start discussing her vision for the album, and her personal brand. It was the next meeting that would become a center piece of my creative outout that year. Not only did we all connect at my studio in the Dogpatch, we also really jelled on a idea that was just a sketch.

The idea was simple. Let;s let the user color in a animatied coloring book while it was playing. People could image "Our Bright Future" as a positive one or a cynical one. It still works well today.
